We have to deal of course not with what Thales really taught, but with what Cicero thought he taught; and the answer is such as Cicero supposed an Epicurean would have made. In line 11 Cicero says that Thales taught that aquam esse initium rerum, and that deum eam mentem esse, which created all things out of water. He must have thought then that deum and mentem were identical, denoting the creating power as distinguished from aqua, the matter. Now the Epicurean’s objections to almost all the views commented upon in the following summary is simply that we cannot conceive of God or mind without sensation, or without a body for this purpose: cf. l. 20, quasi aut a'e'r sine ulla forma deus esse possit &c.; l. 31, aperta simplexque mens, nulla re adiuncta, qua sentire possit, sugere intellegentiae nostrae vim et nationem videtur,· 41, 33, alr . . . quem sensum labere potest aut quam seermam dei?
